<section id="modern-challenges-safety" class="reveal">
  <h2>Rare but Real: Adverse Events in Focus</h2>
  <p>Vaccine safety concerns, while statistically rare, are not baseless. Myocarditis and pericarditis following mRNA COVID-19 vaccines, particularly Pfizer-BioNTech and Moderna, have been documented predominantly in young males after their first or second dose. A 2023 study in JAMA Cardiology reported an incidence rate of 2.7 cases per 100,000 doses in males aged 16-29, with a proposed mechanism involving an overactive immune response to the mRNA-encoded spike protein triggering cardiac inflammation (Oster et al., JAMA Cardiology, 2023; n=1,626 cases).</p>
  <p>Context matters. The risk of myocarditis from COVID-19 infection itself is significantly higher—estimated at 11 cases per 100,000 infections in the same age group—than from vaccination (Boehmer et al., MMWR, 2023; n=3.2 million). Still, for affected individuals, the adverse event is neither negligible nor abstract, and dismissing it as such risks alienating those seeking honest dialogue.</p>
  <p>Other rare events, like thrombosis with thrombocytopenia syndrome linked to adenoviral vector vaccines (e.g., AstraZeneca), have incidence rates below 1 per 100,000 doses but have led to fatalities in isolated cases (Greinacher et al., NEJM, 2021; n=39 cases). These risks, though minimal compared to disease burden, demand rigorous post-marketing surveillance.</p>
</section>

