<section id="coverage-gaps" class="reveal">
  <h2>Global Coverage Gaps: A Persistent Threat</h2>
  <p>Even as science grapples with efficacy and safety, access remains a critical barrier. In 2024, 14.3 million children globally missed all routine vaccinations, classified as "zero-dose children," with little improvement from 14.5 million in 2023 (UNICEF, 2024). Measles, a disease preventable by a highly effective vaccine, saw cases surge to 10.3 million in 2023, a 20% increase from the prior year, with outbreaks worsening into 2025 (WHO, 2024).</p>
  <p>These gaps are not merely logistical. They reflect systemic failures in health infrastructure, compounded by vaccine hesitancy fueled by misinformation and, in some cases, justified skepticism about inconsistent public health messaging. The result is a resurgence of preventable diseases, undermining decades of progress.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"Measles cases reached 10.3 million in 2023, a 20% increase from 2022, with outbreaks intensifying into 2025." — WHO, 2024</p></aside>

<section id="forward-solutions" class="reveal">
  <h2>Fixing Flaws: The Path Ahead</h2>
  <p>Addressing vaccine limitations requires neither blind defense nor wholesale rejection, but targeted innovation. For waning efficacy, next-generation vaccines—such as pan-coronavirus formulations targeting conserved viral regions—are in development, with early trials showing promise against multiple SARS-CoV-2 variants (Cohen et al., Nature, 2025; n=1,200 participants). Annual updates, akin to influenza shots, may become standard for certain pathogens, though this demands clearer public communication to manage expectations.</p>
  <p>On safety, enhanced surveillance systems are critical. The Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (VAERS) and similar global databases must prioritize rapid signal detection and transparent reporting, as seen in the quick identification of myocarditis cases post-mRNA rollout (Shimabukuro et al., Vaccine, 2023; n=192 million doses monitored). Tailored dosing or alternative platforms for high-risk demographics, like non-mRNA options for young males, are under exploration.</p>
  <p>Access disparities need urgent action. Initiatives like GAVI Alliance’s 2021-2025 strategy aim to reach 300 million additional children, but funding shortfalls and geopolitical barriers persist (GAVI, 2024). Bridging these gaps is as vital as any laboratory breakthrough.</p>
</section>

<section id="conclusion" class="reveal">
  <h2>Trust Through Honesty</h2>
  <p>Vaccines have reshaped human health, averting 154 million deaths over half a century, a triumph rooted in rigorous science (Ghebreyesus, WHO, 2025). Yet, their future hinges on confronting flaws—waning protection, rare adverse events, and uneven access—with the same rigor that built their legacy. Ignoring these issues to preserve trust is a losing strategy; acknowledging and addressing them is the only way forward.</p>
  <p>The responsibility is dual. Individuals must seek evidence over rhetoric, while institutions must deliver unvarnished data, even when it complicates the narrative. Only through this mutual accountability can immunization remain a pillar of public health.</p>
</section>

